{
  "texts": [
    "Risko and Gilbert define cognitive offloading as \"[t]he use of physical action to alter the information processing requirements of a task so as to reduce cognitive demand\" (2016, p. 677), while for Kirsty Armitage and colleagues, it amounts to agents \"[m]aking use of external manipulations or artefacts to intentionally reduce the internal demand of a task\" (2020, p. 2).",
    "Since paradigm cases of offloading are mediated by actions that are under the agent's control, this gives agential intention a crucial role in a wide range of cognitive capacities beyond those typically implicated in locomotion-guidance.",
    "Notice also that acts of offloading count as expressions of cognitive agency (if at all) in virtue of their wider environmental effects, to which the bodily movements involved relate according to norms of practical rationality as means to ends.",
    "Writing out a numeral in a long division problem is a means to solving the problem, placing an empty glass bottle by the door is a means of remembering, when the time comes, to take it to the recycling bin.",
    "Moreover, as these and the other examples discussed above show, the end that the agent has in taking these means is distinctly cognitive."
  ]
}